		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2015"></a><br><code>sle2015/paper04</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>A combined formal model for relational context-dependent roles</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ThomasKühn.html">Thomas Kühn</a>, <a href="../profile/StephanBöhme.html">Stephan Böhme</a>, <a href="../profile/SebastianGötz.html">Sebastian Götz</a>, <a href="../profile/UweAßmann.html">Uwe Aßmann</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814255">10.1145/2814251.2814255</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a coherent role-based modeling language that combines relational and context-dependent roles.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It develops a formal model with constraints/definitions to precisely characterize the language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The language includes well-defined constraints that act as static semantic checks over role models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> Role-based modeling is treated as a domain-specific modeling language for complex systems.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
